{"success": true, "message": "Fetched question.", "data": {"showTimer": true, "showAttemptInsight": true, "playSounds": true, "dontShowCorrectAnswerImmediately": false, "_id": "615454d7fab26d7511617266", "type": "singleCorrect", "level": null, "category": null, "approximateTimeRequired": null, "imageBaseUrl": null, "helperText": null, "source": "NTAS1", "classes": [], "exams": ["615d76e4c52ffa3c944600e1"], "subjects": ["615d708dbd4a37c4058ee5a8"], "chapters": ["615d6fed2b295b085ab6eb9a"], "topics": [], "concepts": [], "microConcepts": [], "questionLabels": [{"title": "NTA Abhyas Paper", "value": "80", "isVisible": true}], "previousYearPapers": [], "question": {"text": "Shown in the figure are two point charges <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mi>Q</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi>Q</mi></math> inside the cavity of a spherical shell. The charges are kept near the surface of the cavity on opposite sides of the centre of the shell. If <math><msub><mrow><mi>\u03c3</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></math> is the surface charge on the inner surface and <math><msub><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></math> net charge on it and <math><msub><mrow><mi>\u03c3</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math> the surface charge on the outer surface and <math><msub><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math> net charge on it then:<br />\r<br />\r<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn-question-pool.getmarks.app/nta_abhyas/neet/images/ci/image21-d1008db0-5f7e-4ab3-86ed-1247ca3cbeee.jpg\" style=\"max-width:100%; object-fit:contain\" style=\"height: 95px; width: 100px;\" />", "image": null}, "options": [{"id": "lR5LU", "text": "<math><msub><mrow><mi>\u03c3</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mi>&nbsp;</mi><msub><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math> , <math><msub><mrow><mi>\u03c3</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mi>&nbsp;</mi><msub><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>", "image": null, "isCorrect": false}, {"id": "aSdgQ", "text": "<math><msub><mrow><mi>\u03c3</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>\u2260</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mi>\u00a0</mi><msub><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math> ,    <math><msub><mrow><mi>\u03c3</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>\u2260</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mi>\u00a0</mi><msub><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>", "image": null, "isCorrect": false}, {"id": "cXDCB", "text": "<math><msub><mrow><mi>\u03c3</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>\u2260</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><msub><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>\u2260</mo><mn>0</mn></math> ,    <math><msub><mrow><mi>\u03c3</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>\u2260</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mi>\u00a0</mi><msub><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>\u2260</mo><mn>0</mn></math>", "image": null, "isCorrect": false}, {"id": "X3cR8", "text": "<math><msub><mrow><mi>\u03c3</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>\u2260</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mi>&nbsp;</mi><msub><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math> , <math><msub><mrow><mi>\u03c3</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mi>&nbsp;</mi><msub><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>", "image": null, "isCorrect": true}], "correctValue": null, "solution": {"text": "By the property of electrostatic shielding in the conductors <math><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math> in the conductor.<br /><br />So electric flux = 0 through a dotted Gaussian surface as shown<br /><br /><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn-question-pool.getmarks.app/nta_abhyas/neet/images/ci/image22-e4cb0a07-8125-4bb7-9b03-a1511267f028.jpg\" style=\"max-width:100%; object-fit:contain\" /><br /><br />The net enclosed charge through Gaussian surface = 0<br /><br /><math><mo>\u21d2</mo></math> Net charge <math><msub><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></math> on the inner surface = 0 but the equal and opposite induced charge on the surface will be distributed non uniformly on the inner surface<br /><br />So, <math><msub><mrow><mi>\u03c3</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math><br /><br /><math><mo>\u2235</mo><msub><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math> on the inner surface<br /><br />So, net charge <math><msub><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math> on the outer surface as conductor is neutral but <math><mo>\u2235</mo></math> outer surface is free from any electric field so no charge density exists on the outer surface. So, <math><msub><mrow><mi>\u03c3</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math> .", "image": null}, "videoSolution": null, "numericalLowerLimit": null, "numericalUpperLimit": null, "cpyqbSubjects": ["61bb58181213731910ea0b70", "61c055eae8ce0dc8a5c62d33", "616057750283de43c87e3e1b", "61964fe0a5a5260118868021", "61964f81a5a526011886801d", "629f39e4ac11b26562e0625b", "616057920283de43c87e3e1e", "615f0c729476412f48314dab", "61a8a2c2e8ce0dc8a5c62d2d", "629105adee9e3ae00d63352b", "629f385f263330a77be9fa7d", "616056cd0283de43c87e3e15", "616057190283de43c87e3e18", "62962075e7f8e9ac4daeafd7", "64d50bd73df7f4a7f3017f6f", "66b79b34d4b564dfab4f94cc", "678ea9a09cc79e5f592bdc11", "67fa5fef4468eb1307ceb0ad", "6807d2ad647479b8e8696479"], "cpyqbChapters": ["616024041a305c0e66419287", "61602405c04b6efc2d30aed2", "61964c87b2e3ece4a3ae08f5", "61c089968f11857e2cc22ac4", "61964c88aedbe61edbf4a8ad", "6160240548aa12a5f67c1a13", "61bb8218a1451a3af02543bc", "61e7bd7581a69b0b3a599b78", "61602402632932165bf0ef64", "61602407c6302cf0196ff8b1", "629109ecd5